Why America Is Not Allowed to Reelect President Bush
I have never particularly engaged myself politically, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Because of my opposition to him, I was demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in the year 2000 with a campaign promise of a foreign policy of "humbly."
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preemptive war—and the invasion of Iraq—and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the ballot boxes, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
They have, however, also led to the suspension of the critical process so indispensable to democracy—the comprehensive and honest discussion of pending issues.
Bush silenced the criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11th, he has succeeded in suppressing any dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played directly into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not it.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11th, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America emerged all over the world.
These have given way to widespread resentment.
Clearly more people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush often claims that terrorists hate Americans for what they are—a freedom-loving people—and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day—perhaps twenty times as many.
Nor was the torture of prisoners at the Abu Ghraib prison the work of a few "bad apples."
She was part of a system established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld for handling detainees.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the attacks of September 11th.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush has used this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign is based on the assumption that people ultimately don't care about the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something is not right with America if we fall for it.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with September 11th, even though the September 11th Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly determined that no such connection existed.
One wants to scream: "Wake up, America."
Don't you realize that we're being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from the beginning - if it ever comes to an end.
It was a war of one's own decision, not out of necessity.
Moreover, America entered the war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America had gone to war to liberate Iraq.
But one cannot impose democracy on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
But America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we passively watched as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If we had really been concerned about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the oil ministry, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they resorted to methods—such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners—that shocked and humiliated the population, thereby inciting bitterness and anger.
The retreats and missteps of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protégé with a reputation as a "strong man"—a decision far from democratic.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large part of the western part of the country was left to the rebels. Prospects for the conduct of free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused immeasurable damage to America, weakened its military strength, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an overwhelming impression of strength.
Not today anymore.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war so far amount to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush prodded John Kerry to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently, and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But this will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats have desperately warned Bush not to march into Iraq.
He ignored her.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the supreme commander would endanger US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should pause for a moment and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection is likely to raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy behavior qualify him to remain Commander in Chief of America?
